 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usanterre.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Santerre</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/11/01 10:23:03 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Druid PvP tips</span><hr size=1> Gallatin, you vile NEWT!<br>
<br>
I've made a char on SZ and also am up to 9th.  Druid, team good.  I can share with you some of my experiences:<br>
<br>
When running around somewhere where ganking is a possibility, keep your target bar empty.  When someone casts on you, hit 'c' to con them.  If they are red, quickly gate.<br>
<br>
Those that will attack you will seldom do so without a major advantage.  Of the 8 or so times I have been PK'd so far, only one has not been by a single caster that was red to me (once I was nuked for 237 when I had 170hp).  The other time, my group was ambushed by a crafty group of gnomes.  They managed to snare our puller with multiples incoming, snared me and sicced four pets on me, and nuked our cleric to paste.  Our wizard took one down before they focused on him.<br>
<br>
Expect attack most frequently by a zone.  Thankfully, it is usually ez to escape.  Anywhere safe (crushbone for goods) will be so overcamped as to be not worth going to.<br>
<br>
When soloing in hostile territory, ALWAYS invis/hide while medding, and try to put terrain between you and any frequent routes of travel.<br>
<br>
Your chances of walking into Crushbone and surviving are not terrible - a lot of goods stupidly are trying to co-exist with newts.  Of course, there are also folks like me...  Anyway, your chance of getting an SBS is near-0 as the trainer hill is frequently the site of major KS battles - between goods.  The going price on an SBS is about 30pp.<br>
<br>
At our levels, everything seems to stick on everyone.  Once people get resist gear, it will be a different story. <p><BR><br><B><I><img src="http://www.druidmail.com/santerre2.gif">Santerre.</I></B></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usarvenosttz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>SarvenostTZ</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/11/01 12:43:55 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Druid PvP tips</span><hr size=1> On buff order, there are a couple of different schools that I've heard of, and it depends on how you play.<br>
<br>
Some people put SoW at the top of the list, then go in order from most to least. (After SoW, cast Firefist, then begin buffing) The advantage to this method is this: If you get snared, it overwrites SoW, it does not stack with it. This makes it easy to dispel the snare, re-sow, and continue the fight. It also leaves a buff slot open close to the top (click Firefist off), in case someone casts something on you you simply MUST get off, you only lose your SoW getting to it. This method is reccommended if you want to try to stay and fight it out if things start to go bad.<br>
<br>
Others use Firefist to open a slot at the top of their buff list, then buff least important to most important, with SoW and your resists at the end. Problem here is: You're relying on your resists to save you. If someone lands that Snare on you, you're gonna have to dispel all your buffs to get it off (Yeah, right), or Gate. I've seen both strategies used effectively at high levels, but honestly, I don't know which would have more application on SZ in it's current state. Probably option #1, because if someone snares you, it's gonna land, and you're gonna need to get it off (or run, but we'll assuming you might want to make it harder on your opponent than casting snare to run you off).<br>
<br>
Used to be that you also had to keep your Skin spell at the top of your buff list, because there were a few DoTs (especially Necro Dots 44+) that would overwrite it, though this was patched a few patches ago. About leaving a slot open: Do it. SKs love Engulfing Darkness, and if you don't leave a place for it, it's going at the end of your list, and you're gonna end up gating. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/upinepath.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Pinepath</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/11/01 2:27:26 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> swarm resists</span><hr size=1> I hardly think the swarm line is *bugged*.  some lines of spells are harder to resist than others.  How often do you resist a lifetap or harm touch if you are even con to attacker?<br>
<br>
GZ even mentioned, back when the DOT 2/3 damage nerf was put in, that one advantage druids still had when DOT kiting was the swarm line was very difficult to resist.  He didn't say WHY it was made that way, but I don't think the guy in charge of spells at the time was unaware of the resistance and reasons for it of the spell line. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utudamorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tudamorf</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://lag999.homestead.com/files/biggrin.gif width=15 height=15 BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/11/01 3:09:48 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://lag999.homestead.com/files/rtfm.gif width=100 height=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: swarm resists</span><hr size=1> Pinepath says:  <b><i>I hardly think the swarm line is *bugged*.</b></i><br>
<br>
Was a pun intended?  :)<br>
<br>
Well, you do sort of have a point in that traditionally an insects spell would have a low save.  But in this case I would lean towards calling it a bug because it appears that every DoT spell that neither has initial damage nor a stat debuff has this "feature".  If Verant/Sony/whatnot actually had a clue and realized how it works, there's a good chance it would be nerfed (personal opinion). <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uaeelebpdm.showPublicProfile?language=EN>AeelebPDM</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>PvPMod- The Tactician</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/11/01 9:06:48 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://users.ev1.net/~chawk/eq/aeelebepic.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: swarm resists</span><hr size=1> As a druid your swarm series is your best friend. I've parsed my logs after editing out resists on mobs and the chances of having winged death resisted on a player are about even as winning the lottery while getting struck by lightning. <br>
<br>
One very viable tactic on the other Zeks is to buff your opponent with quick casting trash buffs like Skin Like Wood or See Invis, then throw on your DoT and lay waste. That can't be done on SZ because of the hard coding, but at the same time they seem to have made cancel magic same team only as well. That can work to your advantage as nothing sucks more than being debuffed, especially when spells are going to be your main source for HPS and resists on a new server.<br>
<br>
Buff order is very important if they do enable dispelling for other targets. My buffing is usually bladecoat, ROTG, resist magic, mask of the hunter, SoW, potg. I keep those buffs up 24/7 on TZ and they're in order of importance that I view. For a lower level druid with no gear you'll want to keep as many trash buffs as you can like Firefist up on top and bury SoW, resists, HP buff. always order your resists in importance to both the odds of you needing that resist and how good your unbuffed is. if you know the only enemy you're going to be charging is a wizard, PR and DR could go up top as trash buffs.<br>
<br>
at equal or higher level to your enemies with little to no resists, snare will actually be very useful. Just remember one thing, snare breaks rather quickly with bunches of nukes on players. if you have others with you, your best bet is to snare them and just keep them snared/dot'd while a melee pounds them. nukes will break snare and might allow them to get away.<br>
<br>
